    <br />

    
    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Regression Based Trust Model for Wireless Ad Hoc Networks</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Revathi Venkataraman</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Regression Based Trust<br />AD Hoc Networks</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Sep-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0083</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Wireless ad hoc networks operate in resource constrained environments and it is
observed that the presence of malicious nodes is a critical factor affecting the network
performance. The five essential network security services, namely, authentication, access
control, integrity, confidentiality and non-repudiation are offered by cryptographic
mechanisms. However, these mechanisms fail to detect authorized, legitimate entities
that behave maliciously due to compromise or faulty hardware components. These
security attacks are categorized as internal attacks and they are detected by trust based
security services. Hence, trust based security modeling go hand in hand with cryptographic
services to offer complete security in a network system.
The focus of this work is to propose a generalized Vector Auto Regression (VAR)
based trust-model over routing protocols that can monitor every functional behavior
of a neighboring node and identify those adversaries launching multiple attacks simultaneously
in wireless ad hoc networks. This is done by strengthening the evidence
collection phase prior to trust evaluation. It is a node centric approach where every participating
entity makes individual trust decisions about its neighbors in the network.
The novelty in the approach is to demonstrate the fact that the notion of trust can be
easily incorporated, independent of the underlying network layer routing protocol, in
wireless networks.
The VAR trust model is incorporated over the network layer of the protocol stack
in every participating entity, to identify malicious nodes that launch multiple attacks
in the network. The model captures individual functional behaviors of a neighbor in
an ad hoc network and models them as regression parameters. The trust model is
integrated into two popular ad hoc routing protocols, Ad hoc On-demand Distance
Vector (AODV) routing protocol and Optimized Link State Routing (OLSR) protocol.
AODV is a reactive routing protocol which finds the route to destination on demand
basis whenever there is a need to transfer information. OLSR is a proactive routing
protocol which maintains the route information to all other reachable entities in the
ad hoc network irrespective of the demand to transfer data. The performance evaluations
show that by carefully setting the trust parameters, substantial benefit in terms
of throughput can be obtained with minimal overheads. The computed trust and confidence
values are introduced into the path computation process of the ad hoc routing
protocols. It was observed that the nodes in the network were able to learn the malicious
activities of their neighbors and hence, alternate trustworthy paths are taken to
avoid data loss in the network, with minimal trade-offs in end-to-end packet delay and
routing traffic.
The simulation results were further empirically tested by implementing the VAR
model in a real wireless ad hoc testbed. The laptops with Linux operating systems
serve as ad hoc nodes. The experimental results show the feasibility of implementing
trust models over real ad hoc network deployments. It was shown that amidst 40%
malicious nodes, the throughput of the network is greater than 75% with the end-toend
packet delay higher by 0.1msec than the default AODV and OLSR protocols.
Finally, the proposed model is also implemented over a dynamic, state of the art,
Backpressure Collection Protocol (BCP) in sensor networks which have limited computation
power, battery life, bandwidth and memory. It was shown that the VAR model
is also suited for such resource-constraint networks. Generally, backpressure scheduling
is known for being throughput-optimal. However, it is usually assumed that nodes
cooperate with each other to forward the network traffic. In the presence of malicious
nodes, the throughput optimality no longer holds and this affects the network performance
in collection tree applications of sensor networks. VAR model is applied to
embed trust into the link weights, making it more likely for trusted links to be schedviii
uled. This work is also evaluated in a real sensor network testbed and shown that BCP
with trust offers approximately 75% throughput and ensures reliable routing, with a
small trade-off in the end-to-end packet delay and retransmission counts amidst 40%
malicious nodes.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/8977">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/8977</a></td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Appears in Collections:</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="/dspace/handle/123456789/6855">Ph.D - Thesis  </a><br/></td></tr>
